Subgradient method

For L1 regularization, the subgradient descent method gives

xt+1=xt−η∂F1(xt)

where ∂F1(x)i∋∇f(x)i+λsgnxi. For simplicity, we assume equality.

 
xxxxxxxxxx
8.2 μs
SG_const1 (generic function with 1 method)
 
xxxxxxxxxx
86.2 μs

For L2 regularization, the method is simpler since ∥⋅∥22 is differentiable.

xt+1=xt−η∂F2(xt)

where ∂F2(x)=∇f(x)+2λx

Proximal Gradient

Define Proximal Gradient (PG) method by

xt+1=proxλh(xt−η∇f(xt))

where h=∥⋅∥1 or ∥⋅∥22.

 
xxxxxxxxxx
6.8 μs

We compute that

proxλ∥⋅∥1(xi)={xi−λxi>λxi+λxi<−λ0−λ≤xi≤λ

(The proof was shown in class.)

 
xxxxxxxxxx
8.4 μs

We compute that

proxλ∥⋅∥22(xi)=xi1+2λ

Proof: Since ∥⋅∥22 is differentiable, we may compute the gradient of

arg⁡minz{λ∥z∥22+12∥z−x∥22}

directly. It is a strongly convex function so it is minimized where the gradient is zero.

0=∇z(λ∥z∥22+12∥z−x∥22)=2λz+(z−x)=(1+2λ)z−x

Therefore

z=x1+2λ.◻

Proximal Gradient with Heavy Ball Momentum

The Heavy Ball Momentum method is traditionally defined as

xt+1=xt−η∇(f+λR)(xt)+θ(xt−xt−1)

We can modify our PG method to take advantage of momentum in the following manner:

xt+1=proxλR(xt−η∇f(xt))+θ(x−xt−1)

Proximal Gradient with Nesterov Acceleration

The Nesterov Accelerated Gradient (NAG) method is tradtionally defined by

xt+1=yt−η∇(f+λR)(yt)

and

yt+1=xt+1+tt+3(xt+1−xt)

where y0=x0 and x−1=x0.

To make use of this, we simply replace the first step with a proximal projection:

xt+1=proxλR(yt−η∇f(yt))
